    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-14T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-14T15:00:00-05:00" n="342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.6363 St 2/321: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-14T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 14, 1939—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Guachalla told me last night that in his judgment, in view of recent
                    indeterminate Supreme Court decision, an informal request for arbitration at
                    this time would be received in a very friendly spirit. He suggests exclusion of
                    actual return of the property on the ground that this is desired by neither
                    party and would arouse hostile reactions here. He also suggests that details
                    other than general principle of arbitration be reserved for discussion after his
                    arrival in Washington April 5.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
